          "text": "## Headline finding\n\n**`chatchat.space` is no longer Langchain-Chatchat.** The same team pivoted and now hosts **ClawNet** there — a P2P agent mesh that is a direct competitor to ClawConnect. The OSS Langchain-Chatchat repo and ClawNet are two different products. You have *two* things to compare against.\n\n---\n\n## 1. Langchain-Chatchat (the GitHub repo)\n\n**Not a mesh.** Single-process RAG + agent chatbot. 37.8k stars, but release cadence has stalled (~21 months since v0.3.1 tag). It federates outward only to model backends (OpenAI-compatible HTTP) and MCP tool servers (stdio/SSE). Zero peer-to-peer story.\n\n**Where it's ahead of ClawConnect:**\n- **Deep RAG stack** — FAISS/Milvus/Zilliz/Chroma/ES/pgvector/Relyt adapters, BM25+KNN hybrid retrieval, rerankers, per-file RAG\n- **Document loaders** — PDF w/ OCR fallback, DOCX, PPTX, images, CSV\n- **Tool breadth** — arxiv, wolfram, text2sql, text2promql, search engines, image gen\n- **Streamlit WebUI** with KB management, MCP management, model config pages\n- **OpenAI-compatible FastAPI** so clients are drop-in\n- **MCP client host** with persisted connections (DB-backed, managed via UI)\n\n**Where ClawConnect is ahead:** Everything mesh/P2P/multi-peer — Chatchat has none of it.\n\n## 2. ClawNet (chatchat.space) — the real competitor\n\nBuilt by the same team, pitched as *\"decentralized AI infrastructure — share skills, trade compute, build autonomous swarms.\"* v1.0.0-beta.4, AGPL-3.0, ~101 active nodes. Open-core (OSS layer + paid enterprise tier).\n\n| Dimension | ClawConnect | ClawNet |\n|---|---|---|\n| Peer discovery | Static / mDNS / optional directory | **Kademlia DHT** (global, zero-config) |\n| Encryption | mTLS + SHA-256 fingerprint pinning | Noise Protocol + Ed25519 |\n| Identity | Self-signed X.509 cert fingerprint | Ed25519 keypair |\n| Trust model | Explicit mutual friending (TOFU) | Reputation engine + 7-tier progression |\n| Agent framework | Claude Code adapter only | Framework-agnostic (LangChain/CrewAI/AutoGPT/any HTTP) |\n| Knowledge layer | **None** | Distributed knowledge graph, full-text search |\n| Economic layer | None | On-protocol **bounties + escrow + \"energy\" currency** |\n| Swarm reasoning | None | **\"Swarm Think\"** multi-agent debate as network feature |\n| Streaming | v1: send only | Not specified |\n| UI | CLI + in-Claude channels | HTTP REST on `localhost:3998` |\n| Install friction | `init` + mutual friend exchange | *\"30s to online\"* one-liner |\n\n## 3. What ClawConnect does *better* (defensible positioning)\n\n- **Explicit mutual friending** is a feature, not a gap — ClawNet's open DHT is discoverable by anyone, ClawConnect is a closed trust graph. Different threat model, and for real small-team collaboration yours is safer.\n- **Locality transparency** is cleaner — agents don't know or care about local vs remote, ClawNet's DHT-centric model leaks network topology into agent behavior.\n- **Claude Code channel integration** — ClawNet exposes REST; you have first-class in-session conversational surface via experimental channels.\n- **Fingerprint pinning** is simpler than reputation systems (no gaming, no cold-start).\n\n## 4. Gaps worth closing in ClawConnect\n\n**High-value, fits the mesh story:**\n1. **DHT-based discovery** (optional) — today you have static/mDNS/directory; a global DHT mode for public peers would let you compete on reach\n2. **Streaming (`message:stream`)** — already flagged as future work in adapter README; ClawNet likely has it\n3. **Audit log** for handshakes and trust decisions — THREATS.md already flags this\n4. **Key rotation / revocation** — THREATS.md flags no rotation path; serious gap\n5. **Per-friend rate limits** — circuit breaker for misbehaving peers\n\n**Higher-effort but strategic:**\n6. **Distributed knowledge layer** — even a simple CRDT-backed shared note graph between friends would be a huge differentiator. Don't need a full DHT knowledge graph; a shared conversation + artifact store across friends is a real feature.\n7. **Cross-peer tool federation** — right now tools are local, A2A is text-negotiated. A typed capability advertisement (signed by peer) would let Alice call Bob's `read_file` as a tool rather than asking in prose.\n8. **Swarm reasoning primitive** — a single \"fanout to N peers, aggregate replies\" adapter tool is a few days of work and maps directly to ClawNet's \"Swarm Think\" marketing claim.\n9. **Web dashboard** — ClawNet's REST + LC-Chatchat's Streamlit UI both beat you here. Mesh visualization, thread history, friend management in a browser.\n10. **Framework-agnostic adapter story** — you're Claude-Code-only today. A thin HTTP adapter so LangChain/CrewAI agents can be peers would widen TAM overnight.\n\n**Deliberately *don't* copy:**\n- The tier/energy/bounty economy — it's a vibe-marketing layer, not a technical moat, and tokenomics adds complexity + legal exposure for little user value.\n- Global DHT *as default* — trust-on-first-use against the whole internet is a worse product than explicit friending for most real teams.\n\n---\n\nWant me to save this competitive map to memory, or dig deeper on any one of these (e.g., inspect ClawNet's open-source code on GitHub to see what the DHT actually looks like)?",
