          "type": "assistant",
          "text": "Happy to. Here's a walkthrough of each gap with enough depth to file issues against. I've grouped them by scope and included effort/risk so you can prioritize.\n\n---\n\n## Quick wins (low effort, high clarity)\n\n### 1. Per-friend rate limits\n- **What**: Token bucket keyed on friend fingerprint, alongside existing per-agent and global buckets.\n- **Why it matters**: Today if a single friend misbehaves (bug, compromise, runaway agent), they drain the *global* bucket and cause collateral damage to all other friends. THREATS.md already flags this (Threat 4). Rate limiting isn't a security boundary, but it is a blast-radius boundary.\n- **How**: Extend the token-bucket module to accept `(friendFingerprint, agentName)` as composite key. Allocate a default bucket per friend on first request. Add `[friends.<handle>] rateLimit = \"100/hour\"` override in `friends.toml`.\n- **Effort**: Small (~0.5 day).\n- **Risk**: None significant. Pure additive.\n\n### 2. Audit log\n- **What**: Append-only log of trust-relevant events: handshakes (accept/deny/auto-decision), friend add/remove, cert pin changes, config reloads, rejected requests with reason.\n- **Why it matters**: Today if someone asks \"why did my peer auto-accept a handshake last Tuesday?\", there's no answer. No forensics, no compliance story, no way to detect a quiet compromise.\n- **How**: JSONL file at `$CLAW_CONNECT_HOME/audit.log`. One struct per event with timestamp, event type, actor fingerprint, outcome, reason. Rotate by size or day. Later: a `claw-connect audit` CLI for querying.\n- **Effort**: Small (~1 day).\n- **Risk**: PII/sensitive data in logs — be explicit about what *not* to log (message bodies).\n\n### 3. Streaming (`message:stream`)\n- **What**: Implement the A2A v1.0 `message:stream` endpoint alongside `message:send`. Replies arrive token-by-token, not all-at-once.\n- **Why it matters**: Already flagged as v1 future work in `a2a-claude-code-adapter/README.md`. Without streaming,