any trust.\n- **Why it matters**: ClawNet's single biggest product claim is \"30s to online, auto-joins global mesh.\" You have mDNS (LAN only) and directory (requires a server). DHT fills the \"public peer, no server\" slot. Critical: **discovery ≠ trust.** You still need to explicit-friend before any messages flow — the DHT just helps you *find* the candidate.\n- **How**: Add `src/discovery/dht-provider.ts` using `@libp2p/kad-dht`. Peer announces `(fingerprint, endpoint, handle)`; lookups return peer records. Explicit opt-in via `server.toml`. First connection from an unknown DHT peer hits your existing connection-request handshake — no bypass.\n- **Effort**: Medium-large (~1–2 weeks). libp2p is a heavy dependency; consider alternatives like a lightweight custom DHT or Hyperswarm.\n- **Risk**: Sybil/spam at discovery layer. Mitigate by requiring proof-of-work on DHT announces, or by keeping DHT behavior strictly \"find candidates, don't auto-connect.\"\n\n---\n\n## Protocol expansion (mesh story)\n\n### 6. Cross-peer tool federation\n- **What**: A peer advertises a typed tool surface (JSONSchema) in its agent card. Remote peers can invoke those tools via a structured RPC, not prose negotiation.\n- **Why it matters**: Today, if Alice wants Bob's agent to read a file, she types \"please read X and send it back\" and Bob's agent reads the prose, decides to call `read_file`, and replies. This is unreliable (prose → intent is lossy) and unobservable. Typed tool federation = Alice's agent sees `bob.read_file` as a regular MCP tool and calls it directly. This is the single biggest UX leap available to you.\n- **How**:\n  - Extend agent card with `tools: [{name, description, inputSchema}]`.\n  - New A2A method `tools/call` that wraps an invocation.\n  - Adapter exposes remote peers' tools with namespace prefix (`bob__read_file`).\n  - Per-friend-per-tool permission in `friends.toml` (`allowedTools = [\"read_file\"]` or `\"*\"`).\n- **Effort**: Medium-large (~1–2 weeks).\n- **Risk**: Big. This is a cross-machine capability delegation — exactly the thing you avoided in v1 on purpose. Permission model must be explicit. Default should be tools DISABLED until friended + scoped.\n\n### 7. Swarm reasoning primitive\n- **What**: A single adapter tool that fans a message to N peers, collects their replies within a timeout, and presents them as a unified context block.\n- **Why it matters**: Directly counters ClawNet's \"Swarm Think\" marketing claim. Useful for real work — \"ask all three engineering peers for their take on this RFC, then summarize\" is a pattern people want.\n- **How**: New adapter tool `fanout(peers: string[], text: string, timeout_ms: number)`. Implementation: parallel `message:send` to each peer, wait for replies (each arrives as a channel event keyed to the same `context_id`), wrap all responses in a single summary block when the waiter resolves.\n- **Effort**: Small-medium (~2–4 days). Mostly adapter work; daemon already supports multi-peer.\n- **Risk**: Low. Good introductory feature — easy win that counters the loudest ClawNet claim.\n\n### 8. Distributed knowledge layer (phased)\n- **What**: A shared persistent store across friends — shared notes, conversation history, artifacts. Phase 1: per-friend-group append-only log of artifacts. Phase 2: CRDT-merged shared documents. Phase 3: vector search over the shared corpus.\n- **Why it matters**: ClawNet's \"distributed knowledge graph\" is their second-biggest claim. Langchain-Chatchat has deep RAG but single-machine. You have neither. Even a simple shared-artifact store would be meaningful.\n- **How** (Phase 1 only — rest should be separate issues):\n  - Introduce `friends_groups.toml` — named subsets of friends.\n  - New A2A method `artifact:publish` and `artifact:query`.\n  - Local SQLite store indexed by `(group, artifact_id, author_fingerprint, timestamp)`.\n  - Adapter tools: `publish_artifact`, `search_artifacts`.\n- **Effort**: Phase 1: Large (~2–3 weeks). Phase