            "content": "# Key rotation and revocation\n\n## Context\n\nToday, peer identity is a self-signed X.509 certificate valid for 100 years with\nno rotation or revocation story. If a key leaks, the only recovery path is:\n\n1. Run `claw-connect init` again to generate a new identity\n2. Tell every friend out-of-band to remove the old fingerprint and pin the new one\n\nThis does not scale past a handful of friends. Friends who miss the update\nkeep pinning a compromised key. `THREATS.md` flags the absence of rotation\nand revocation as known gaps.\n\nReal products need a rotation story. This task delivers one without breaking\nthe core principle that trust is explicit.\n\n## Proposed approach — phased\n\n### Phase 1: key rotation\n\nA peer can replace its identity keypair and have friends auto-update their pin.\n\n- New A2A control message `identity:rotate` signed by the *old* private key,\n  carrying the new public key / cert and a timestamp\n- Friends who receive it verify the signature against the currently pinned\n  fingerprint, then pin the new fingerprint\n- Rotation announcements are rate-limited (one per friend per day) to limit\n  damage if an attacker gains the old key\n- Operator UX: `claw-connect identity rotate` generates the new keypair,\n  broadcasts to all known friends, and writes the new cert to disk\n- Friends who miss the broadcast (offline at rotation time) accept a later\n  replay as long as the signature still verifies against their pinned\n  fingerprint\n\n### Phase 2: revocation\n\nA peer can signal to its friends that a specific fingerprint should no longer\nbe trusted.\n\n- New A2A control message `identity:revoke` signed by the revoking peer's\n  current key, naming the fingerprint to revoke\n- Friends add the fingerprint to a local revocation list and refuse any\n  future mTLS handshake from it\n- Use case: an operator learns their old key leaked before they could rotate;\n  they rotate first (Phase 1), then revoke the old fingerprint (Phase 2)\n\n### Phase 3 (separate task): gossip propagation\n\nFriends-of-friends learn about revocations via opt-in gossip. Out of scope\nhere — filed as a follow-up once Phase 1 and 2 are stable.\n\n## Acceptance criteria (Phase 1 + 2)\n\n- `claw-connect identity rotate` produces a new cert, stores the old cert as\n  a signing witness, and broadcasts a signed rotation announcement\n- Friends update their pin on receipt and log the change to the audit log\n- A rotation announcement with an invalid signature is rejected and logged\n- `claw-connect identity revoke <fingerprint>` broadcasts a signed revocation\n- Friends refuse mTLS from a revoked fingerprint immediately and log the\n  rejection\n- The `identity:rotate` and `identity:revoke` messages are idempotent and\n  replay-safe (timestamp + nonce)\n- Unit + integration tests for: happy-path rotation, tampered rotation,\n  replayed rotation, revocation enforcement\n\n## Effort\n\nLarge — 2 weeks for Phases 1 + 2.\n\n## Open questions / risks\n\n- **Ceremonial key continuity**: should we require the operator to confirm\n  rotation out of band (e.g., verify a short code over Signal) before friends\n  accept? Pure signature-based acceptance is vulnerable if the old key is\n  already in the attacker's hands. One option: require rotation within a\n  short grace window after `init`, and any later rotation needs friend-side\n  confirmation.\n- **Clock skew**: timestamps in rotation messages need a tolerance window;\n  pick a defensible default (5 min).\n- **Rotation frequency abuse**: cap rotations to one per friend per day to\n  prevent a compromised key from rotating faster than operators can react.\n\n## File pointers\n\n- `packages/claw-connect/src/identity.ts` — identity generation\n- `packages/claw-connect/src/outbound-tls.ts` — fingerprint pinning\n- `packages/claw-connect/src/middleware.ts` — friend validation\n- `packages/claw-connect/THREATS.md` — rotation / revocation gap\n",
