            "content": "# DHT-based discovery (optional provider)\n\n## Context\n\nDiscovery today offers three providers:\n\n- **Static** — hand-curated list in `server.toml`\n- **mDNS** — LAN-only via Bonjour/Avahi\n- **Directory** — centralized directory server (requires operator)\n\nNone covers the \"public peer, no central server\" case. ClawNet's biggest product\nclaim is a Kademlia DHT that gives 30-second onboarding to a global mesh. We\nlose on reach when someone wants to be findable on the open internet without\nrunning a directory.\n\n**Critical design constraint:** discovery does not confer trust. Finding a peer\nvia the DHT only tells you an endpoint and a claimed handle. The mutual\nfriending step is unchanged — first contact still goes through the existing\nconnection-request handshake.\n\n## Proposed approach\n\nNew provider at `packages/claw-connect/src/discovery/dht-provider.ts`.\n\n- Use an off-the-shelf Kademlia implementation (libp2p KAD-DHT, Hyperswarm, or\n  a small custom implementation — decision out of scope for the task brief,\n  see Open questions)\n- Peer announces a signed record `(fingerprint, endpoint, handle, timestamp,\n  agent-card URL)` under key `H(fingerprint)`\n- Lookups return matching records; caller verifies the signature against the\n  fingerprint before trusting the endpoint\n- Records expire after 24 hours; announcers re-publish on an interval\n- Opt-in via `server.toml`:\n\n  ```toml\n  [discovery.dht]\n  enabled = true\n  bootstrap = [\"dht.example:4001\", \"...\"]\n  announce = true      # publish our own record\n  ```\n\n## Acceptance criteria\n\n- DHT provider registers as the fourth discovery provider\n- Disabled by default; enabling requires explicit config\n- Announcements are signed by the announcer's identity key\n- Lookups verify the signature before returning a result\n- A discovered peer still goes through the existing connection-request\n  handshake before any messages flow\n- `claw-connect discovery find <handle>` CLI for manual lookups\n- Integration test: two peers with no shared config find each other via a\n  bootstrap node and successfully complete a handshake\n\n## Effort\n\nLarge — 1 to 2 weeks.\n\n## Open questions / risks\n\n- **Library choice**: libp2p is the full-featured option but adds a heavy\n  dependency. Hyperswarm is lighter but less battle-tested for this use case.\n  A tiny custom Kademlia is feasible but a maintenance burden. Evaluate before\n  committing.\n- **Sybil / spam**: open DHTs are flood targets. Mitigations:\n  - Require proof-of-work on announcements\n  - Cap record size\n  - Treat DHT results as *candidates*, never as trusted peers\n- **Bootstrap trust**: the bootstrap node list is a bootstrapping concern.\n  Publish a default list signed by the project, but let operators override.\n- **Privacy**: announcing on a public DHT broadcasts that you exist and your\n  endpoint. Offer a \"private DHT\" mode (closed bootstrap set) for people who\n  want discovery without public exposure.\n- **NAT traversal**: discovery returns an endpoint, but if the peer is behind\n  a symmetric NAT the endpoint is useless. This task does not solve NAT\n  traversal; document the limitation and recommend Tailscale / ngrok / VPS.\n\n## File pointers\n\n- `packages/claw-connect/src/discovery/registry.ts` — provider interface\n- `packages/claw-connect/src/discovery/mdns-provider.ts` — reference provider\n- `packages/claw-connect/src/discovery/directory-provider.ts` (if present) —\n  another reference\n",
