          "type": "assistant",
          "text": "\n\nGreat questions — let me take these one at a time.\n\n## Will the CRDT approach break down at 100 members?\n\n**The OR-Set for membership: totally fine at 100.** The state is just a map of 100 entries, each with a small set of UUID tags. Full state exchange is maybe 50KB. Merge is milliseconds. No problem.\n\n**The note sync is where it gets uncomfortable.** The current design sends a list of all note IDs on reconnect so each side can figure out what's missing. With 100 active agents publishing notes:\n\n- 100 people × 5 notes/day × 30 days = 15,000 notes\n- ID list alone is ~600KB per sync\n- Every reconnect with every peer exchanges this list\n- A peer who was offline for a week reconnects to 99 peers and does this 99 times\n\nIt still *works* — it's just wasteful. The fix is well-known: use a **Bloom filter** or **Merkle tree** to figure out what's missing without exchanging the full list. But that's an optimization, not a redesign. Phase 1 ships with full-ID-exchange and a comment that says \"swap in Bloom filter when groups exceed ~50 members.\"\n\n**The real scaling wall is fan-out.** When a note is published, the daemon sends it to all reachable members. At 100 members, that's 99 outbound mTLS connections per publish. Sequential fan-out (current design) would be slow; you'd need `Promise.allSettled` for parallel fan-out, and even then you're opening 99 connections from one laptop. At that point you probably want **gossip-based dissemination** — publish to a random subset of K members, they relay to K more, and so on. Epidemic protocols converge in O(log N) rounds. But again, that's an optimization for Phase 2, not a Phase 1 blocker.\n\n**TL;DR:** The design works cleanly up to ~30-50 members. At 100+ it's still correct but needs optimization (Bloom filters for sync, gossip for fan-out). None of these optimizations change the core CRDT model — they just swap out the sync transport underneath it.\n\n## Should we look at Bluesky's AT Protocol or blockchain for identity?\n\nThis is worth thinking carefully about because there are two very different things people mean when they say \"Bluesky\" or \"blockchain\":\n\n### Bluesky's AT Protocol — actually interesting for you\n\nAT Protocol solves a specific problem well: **portable, self-certifying identity that isn't tied to a single server.** Here's what's relevant:\n\n- **DIDs (Decentralized Identifiers)** — your identity is a `did:plc:...` or `did:web:...` string. It's backed by a keypair (like your fingerprints today) but wrapped in a standard that has a whole ecosystem around it.\n- **Key rotation built in** — AT Protocol handles key rotation natively via DID documents. Your DID stays the same even when you rotate keys. This directly solves Task 04 (key rotation/revocation), which is your hardest security task.\n- **Signed data repositories** — every user has a Merkle tree of signed data. This maps cleanly to your signed notes in groups.\n- **No blockchain** — AT Protocol is deliberately not a blockchain. No tokens, no consensus, no gas fees.\n\nThe question is: do you adopt DIDs as your identity layer instead of raw X.509 fingerprints?\n\n**Pros:**\n- Key rotation is solved (DID document updates, not a custom protocol)\n- Portable identity — an agent's identity works across ClawConnect and any other AT-Protocol-compatible system\n- Standards-based — you stop maintaining your own identity/rotation/revocation scheme\n- `did:web` lets you anchor identity to a domain (`did:web:alice.dev`) which is nicer than `sha256:a1b2c3...`\n\n**Cons:**\n- Dependency on the DID/AT ecosystem — more moving parts\n- `did:plc` requires a PLC directory (centralized, run by Bluesky currently)\n- `did:web` requires a web server at the domain\n- Your current TOFU model with raw fingerprints is simpler and has zero external dependencies\n\n### Blockchain — probably not\n\nBlockchain gives you two things: decentralized consensus and a public ledger. For ClawConnect:\n\n- **You