          "text": "Good question — the answer depends on which DID method you pick. There are several, and they have very different infrastructure profiles:\n\n## The options\n\n### `did:key` — host nothing\n\nThe DID literally IS the public key, encoded as a string:\n```\ndid:key:z6MkhaXgBZDvotDkL5257faiztiGiC2QtKLGpbnnEGta2doK\n```\n\n- **Infrastructure: zero.** No server, no directory, no DNS.\n- **Key rotation: impossible.** The key IS the identifier. If you rotate, you get a new DID. Same problem you have today with fingerprints.\n- **Basically what you already have**, just in a standard format. It would let you say \"we use DIDs\" and interop with DID-aware tooling, but it doesn't solve rotation.\n\n### `did:web` — host a static JSON file\n\nThe DID points to a domain, and the DID document lives at a well-known URL:\n```\ndid:web:alice.dev\n→ resolves to https://alice.dev/.well-known/did.json\n```\n\nThe DID document is just JSON:\n```json\n{\n  \"@context\": \"https://www.w3.org/ns/did/v1\",\n  \"id\": \"did:web:alice.dev\",\n  \"verificationMethod\": [{\n    \"id\": \"did:web:alice.dev#key-1\",\n    \"type\": \"Ed25519VerificationKey2020\",\n    \"publicKeyMultibase\": \"z6Mkh...\"\n  }]\n}\n```\n\n- **Infrastructure: a web server.** Any static host works — GitHub Pages, a VPS, Vercel, even S3. It's one JSON file.\n- **Key rotation: update the file.** Swap the public key in the JSON, done. Your DID (`did:web:alice.dev`) stays the same. Peers re-resolve it periodically.\n- **Downside: DNS is the trust root.** Whoever controls `alice.dev` controls the identity. Domain expires → identity hijackable. DNS is also a single point of failure (ICANN, registrars). And it requires every peer to own a domain.\n- **For ClawConnect specifically:** this is awkward because not every user has a domain, and \"buy a domain to use the mesh\" is onboarding friction.\n\n### `did:plc` — Bluesky's method\n\nThis is what Bluesky actually uses. The DID is an opaque string:\n```\ndid: