s unresolvable until you come back and re-publish.\n- **Downside: relatively new.** The spec is from 2024, fewer implementations than `did:web` or `did:plc`.\n- **For ClawConnect specifically:** this maps almost perfectly.\n  - No central server ✓\n  - No domain required ✓\n  - Key rotation without custom protocol ✓\n  - Uses an existing massive infrastructure ✓\n  - Works offline (peers cache resolved DIDs) ✓\n  - Re-publish requirement maps to \"daemon announces while running\" which you'd do anyway for discovery\n\n## My recommendation\n\n**`did:dht` is the natural fit.** Here's how it'd work:\n\n1. `claw-connect init` generates an Ed25519 keypair and publishes a DID document to the Mainline DHT\n2. Your identity is `did:dht:z6Mkh...` — no domain, no server, no directory\n3. Friends pin your DID (not a raw fingerprint). On connect, they resolve the DID via DHT to get your current public key\n4. **Key rotation**: run `claw-connect identity rotate`, it generates a new keypair, updates the DID document in the DHT, and signs the update with the old key. Friends re-resolve and get the new key automatically\n5. The daemon re-publishes the DID document every ~12 hours while running (keeps the DHT record alive)\n6. Friends cache the last-resolved DID document locally, so if the DHT is temporarily unreachable they still have the pinned key\n\n**This replaces Task 04 (key rotation) entirely** — you don't need a custom rotation protocol because DIDs handle it. And it plays nicely with Task 05 (DHT discovery) since you're already touching the DHT layer.\n\nThe catch: you'd need a TypeScript library for `did:dht` resolution and the Mainline DHT. There's [`@web5/dids`](https://github.com/TBD54566975/web5-js) from TBD (Block/Square's Web5 project) which implements `did:dht`, but it's a heavy dependency. Alternatively, Mainline DHT has lightweight clients (`bittorrent-dht` on npm, ~50KB) and the DID document format is just signed JSON — you could wire it yourself.\n\nWant me to 