          "text": "Tasks updated — 04 and 05 are now merged into a single \"DHT identity and discovery\" task using `did:dht` + `bittorrent-dht`. Old files cleaned up.\n\nNow to your question about monetization — this is actually the hardest question for infra-layer projects like this. A few models that fit:\n\n**What works for P2P infra:**\n\n1. **Open-core (what ClawNet claims to do)** — the mesh is open source; you sell enterprise features on top. For ClawConnect that could be:\n   - Managed relay nodes (NAT traversal as a service — peers behind corporate firewalls route through your relays)\n   - Hosted directory / DHT bootstrap as a managed service\n   - Admin dashboard with analytics (who's talking to whom, message volume, latency)\n   - Compliance features (audit log export, SOC2 reports, data residency controls)\n   - SLA-backed uptime for the relay/discovery layer\n\n2. **Hosted mesh (PaaS)** — \"ClawConnect Cloud.\" You run the daemon for teams who don't want to self-host. They get a managed peer identity, always-online presence, and a web dashboard. Free for 3 peers, paid tiers for more. This is the Tailscale model — the protocol is open, the coordination service is the product.\n\n3. **Platform tax on the knowledge layer** — if Task 06 (shared knowledge) gets traction, you could host the storage layer. Free tier: 1GB of shared notes. Paid: more storage, vector search, longer retention, cross-group search.\n\n4. **Agent marketplace / registry** — once the framework-agnostic adapter (Task 08) exists, you could run a directory where people publish agent capabilities. Free to list, paid for verified/promoted listings or priority routing.\n\n**What probably doesn't work:**\n- Tokens / crypto — adds legal complexity, scares enterprise buyers, and you explicitly didn't want to copy ClawNet's incentive economy\n- Per-message pricing — nobody pays for transport once they see the open-source alternative\n- Consulting-only — doesn't scale\n\n**The Tailscale playbook is the closest analog.** WireGuard is open source. Tailscale built a business by making WireGuard effortless: managed coordination server, identity (backed by SSO), admin console, ACLs, audit logs. The mesh itself is free; the control plane is the product. You could do the same: ClawConnect mesh is open source, the control plane (hosted DHT bootstrap, managed relay, admin dashboard, team management) is the paid product.\n\nWant me to write this up as a doc, or is this just thinking-out-loud territory for now?",
