            "content": "# WireGuard transport layer\n\n## Context\n\nClawConnect currently uses mTLS on `:9900` for peer-to-peer encryption. This\nworks but has two problems:\n\n1. **NAT traversal is unsolved.** Peers behind NATs or firewalls cannot accept\n   inbound connections. The current workaround is \"use Tailscale or ngrok\" —\n   which works but adds a dependency and onboarding friction.\n\n2. **Identity is split.** The mTLS layer uses X.509 certificates with SHA-256\n   fingerprints. Task 04 introduces `did:dht` with Ed25519 keys. That's two\n   identity systems. WireGuard also uses Ed25519 — if the transport used\n   WireGuard, the transport key, the DID key, and the DHT key could all be\n   the same keypair. One identity for everything.\n\nReplacing mTLS with WireGuard would unify encryption, authentication, and\nNAT traversal into a single layer, remove the X.509 cert machinery, and\nmake peers reachable without third-party tunneling services.\n\n## Research questions (answer before committing to build)\n\nThis task starts as a research spike. The questions below must be answered\nbefore any implementation begins.\n\n### 1. Userspace WireGuard in Node.js\n\nThe daemon is a Node.js process. Kernel WireGuard requires root and OS-level\nconfig — not suitable for a \"just run the daemon\" developer tool. We need\nuserspace WireGuard.\n\nOptions to evaluate:\n\n- **`boringtun`** — Cloudflare's userspace WireGuard in Rust. Has C FFI.\n  Could be wrapped with `napi-rs` for Node bindings. Battle-tested in\n  production at Cloudflare. Check: are there existing Node bindings? If\n  not, how much work is the FFI wrapper?\n- **`wireguard-go`** — reference userspace implementation in Go. Could be\n  run as a subprocess. Check: can it be embedded, or is it a standalone\n  binary with its own tun device?\n- **`wireguard-js`** or similar — any pure JS/TS/WASM implementation?\n  Unlikely to exist but worth checking.\n- **`@aspect-build/aspect-wireguard`** or any npm packages wrapping\n  WireGuard.\n\nKey question: can we get a WireGuard tunnel running inside the Node process\nwithout root, without a tun device, and without shelling out to a separate\nbinary? If not, what's the minimal sidecar architecture?\n\n### 2. NAT traversal\n\nWireGuard itself does not solve NAT traversal — it just sends UDP packets.\nNAT traversal requires:\n\n- **STUN** — discover your public IP and port mapping. Standard, simple,\n  many public STUN servers available.\n- **Hole punching** — both peers send packets to each other's STUN-discovered\n  endpoints simultaneously. Works for most NATs except symmetric NATs.\n- **Relay (TURN / DERP)** — when hole punching fails (symmetric NATs,\n  corporate firewalls), relay traffic through an intermediary.\n\nQuestions:\n- Can we use existing STUN servers (Google, Cloudflare) or do we need our own?\n- For relay: Tailscale's DERP servers are open source (Go). Could we run one?\n  Or build a simpler relay that just forwards encrypted UDP? What's the\n  hosting cost for a minimal relay?\n- What percentage of real-world NATs allow UDP hole punching? (Tailscale\n  reports ~94% direct connection rate.)\n\n### 3. Shared Ed25519 keypair\n\n`did:dht` uses Ed25519. WireGuard uses Curve25519 (which is the same\nunderlying curve, just a different representation). An Ed25519 signing key\ncan be converted to a Curve25519 key-exchange key deterministically.\n\nQuestions:\n- Is the Ed25519 → Curve25519 conversion well-supported in Node.js?\n  (`libsodium` / `@noble/curves` should have it.)\n- Are there security concerns with using the same key for both signing (DID)\n  and key exchange (WireGuard)? (Generally considered safe for Ed25519 /\n  X25519 but verify.)\n- Does this mean `claw-connect init` generates one Ed25519 keypair that\n  serves as: DID identity, DHT record signing key, AND WireGuard tunnel key?\n\n### 4. Connection establishment\n\nHow do two peers establish a WireGuard tunnel given only each other's DIDs?\n\nProposed flow:\n```\n1. Alice resolves Bob's DID from DHT → gets Bob's public key + endpoint hint\n2. Alice initiates WireGuard handshake to Bob's endpoint\n3. If direct fails → STUN hole-punch attempt\n4. If hole-punch fails → relay through DERP/relay node\n5. WireGuard tunnel established\n6. HTTP traffic (A2A messages) flows inside the tunnel — plain HTTP, no TLS\n   needed since WireGuard provides encryption and authentication\n```\n\nQuestions:\n- Does this flow work? What's the latency for tunnel establishment?\n- Can WireGuard tunnels be ephemeral (established per-conversation) or do\n  they need to be long-lived?\n- How does the daemon manage multiple simultaneous tunnels (one per active\n  friend)?\n\n### 5. What we remove\n\nIf WireGuard replaces mTLS, we can delete:\n\n- X.509 certificate generation (`src/identity.ts` — the cert parts)\n- mTLS server setup (`src/server.ts` — the HTTPS server on `:9900`)\n- Fingerprint pinning (`src/outbound-tls.ts`)\n- Certificate validation in middleware\n\nThe loopback HTTP server on `:9901` stays (local adapters don't need\nencryption). The friend validation middleware stays but checks WireGuard\npublic keys instead of cert fingerprints.\n\n## Proposed architecture (if research validates)\n\n```\n┌──────────────────────────────────────────┐\n│            claw-connect daemon           │\n│                                          │\n│  ┌──────────────────────────────────┐    │\n│  │ WireGuard Manager                │    │\n│  │  - one tunnel per active friend  │    │\n│  │  - Ed25519 → Curve25519 key     │    │\n│  │  - STUN for endpoint discovery   │    │\n│  │  - relay fallback                │    │\n│  └──────────┬───────────────────────┘    │\n│             │                            │\n│  ┌──────────▼───────────────────────┐    │\n│  │ HTTP server (plain, inside       │    │\n│  │ WireGuard tunnel — no TLS)       │    │\n│  │  - same routes as today          │    │\n│  │  - friend auth by WireGuard key  │    │\n│  └──────────────────────────────────┘    │\n│                                          │\n│  ┌──────────────────────────────────┐    │\n│  │ HTTP server (loopback :9901)     │    │\n│  │  - local adapters, unchanged     │    │\n│  └──────────────────────────────────┘    │\n└──────────────────────────────────────────┘\n        │ UDP\n        ▼\n  WireGuard tunnels to friends\n  (direct or via relay)\n```\n\n## Phasing\n\n### Phase 0: Research spike (this task, first deliverable)\n\nAnswer all research questions above. Build a minimal proof-of-concept: two\nNode processes establishing a userspace WireGuard tunnel and exchanging an\nHTTP request through it. No ClawConnect integration — just validate the\nprimitives.\n\nDeliverable: a written report with findings + a working PoC in\n`packages/wireguard-poc/`.\n\n### Phase 1: Optional WireGuard transport\n\nAdd WireGuard as an alternative transport alongside mTLS. Config flag in\n`server.toml`:\n```toml\n[transport]\nmode = \"wireguard\"   # or \"mtls\" (default, backward compat)\n```\n\nBoth modes coexist during migration. Friends can connect via either.\n\n### Phase 2: STUN + relay for NAT traversal\n\nIntegrate STUN hole-punching. Run (or let operators run) a minimal relay\nserver for fallback. Document the relay hosting requirements.\n\n### Phase 3: mTLS deprecation\n\nOnce WireGuard transport is stable, deprecate mTLS. Remove X.509 cert code.\nSingle identity: Ed25519 keypair used for DID, DHT, and WireGuard.\n\n## Acceptance criteria (Phase 0 only)\n\n- Research questions above are answered with evidence, not speculation\n- PoC demonstrates: two Node processes, userspace WireGuard tunnel, HTTP\n  request/response through the tunnel, no root required\n- Written report recommends go/no-go with rationale\n- If go: updated architecture doc for Phases 1-3\n- If no-go: document why and what alternative solves NAT traversal\n\n## Effort\n\nPhase 0 (research + PoC): ~1 week.\nPhases 1-3 (if validated): ~4-6 weeks.\n\n## Open questions / risks\n\n- **Userspace WireGuard maturity in Node:** this may be the blocker. If no\n  good Node.js integration exists and the FFI wrapper is weeks of work,\n  the whole approach may not be worth it versus just documenting \"use\n  Tailscale.\"\n- **Relay hosting cost:** if we run relay nodes, that's recurring infra cost.\n  Could be the seed of the business model (free relay for small usage, paid\n  for guaranteed bandwidth/uptime) or could just be a cost center.\n- **Complexity budget:** this is a major architectural change. The current\n  mTLS stack works. The motivation is primarily NAT traversal and identity\n  unification — make sure those benefits justify the migration cost.\n- **Mobile / browser agents:** WireGuard over UDP doesn't work in browsers.\n  If browser-based agents are ever on the roadmap, you'd need a WebSocket\n  transport anyway. Consider whether this forecloses future client types.\n\n## File pointers\n\n- `packages/claw-connect/src/identity.ts` — current keypair/cert generation\n- `packages/claw-connect/src/server.ts` — current mTLS server\n- `packages/claw-connect/src/outbound-tls.ts` — current fingerprint pinning\n- `packages/claw-connect/src/middleware.ts` — current friend auth\n- Task 04 (`04-dht-identity-and-discovery.md`) — shares Ed25519 keypair story\n",
