        {
          "type": "assistant",
          "text": "It's both a protocol and a runtime — but if you're naming things, it helps to separate them:\n\n**The protocol** is the wire format — how peers discover each other, authenticate, and exchange messages. That's the A2A message types in `a2a.ts`, the handshake flow, the `group:sync` / `note:publish` methods, the DID resolution. It's the spec someone else could implement independently.\n\n**The runtime** is the daemon + adapters — the actual software that implements the protocol. `claw-connect serve`, the mTLS server, the CLI, the Claude Code adapter. It's the reference implementation.\n\nSome projects name these the same (WireGuard is both). Some split them:\n\n| Protocol | Runtime |\n|----------|---------|\n| BitTorrent | qBittorrent, Transmission, Deluge |\n| AT Protocol | Bluesky |\n| Matrix | Element, Synapse |\n| ActivityPub | Mastodon, Misskey |\n| WireGuard | Tailscale, Mullvad |\n\nThe interesting question for you: **do you want other people to build their own implementations?**\n\nIf yes — name the protocol and the runtime separately. The protocol is the standard; your runtime is the reference implementation. Like how AT Protocol is the spec and Bluesky is the app.\n\nIf no (at least not yet) — one name is fine. WireGuard is both the protocol and the implementation, and they split later only if needed.\n\nGiven where you are (early, one implementation, exploring), I'd go with **one name for now** and split later if the protocol takes off. So if you pick \"Reef\" — the protocol is Reef, the CLI is `reef`, the daemon is `reef serve`, and if someone else wants to build a compatible implementation someday they'd say \"it speaks Reef.\"\n\nThe thing that's worth doing now: write down what's protocol (the wire format, message types, DID resolution, group sync) vs what's implementation detail (Express server, TOML config, SQLite storage). That boundary makes the protocol extractable later without a rewrite. Want me to add that to the docs?",
